v>

<div class=3D"section1 gptoolusages padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_USAGES_DF2238=
27500A4ED59FCC8BD01C80A0EF" purpose=3D"gptoolusages"><h2>Usage</h2><ul purp=
ose=3D"gptoolusages">
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_FF990AC946B8410180647859A90539=
7E" conrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/ESRI_USAGE_D365E=
D9C86D742EC9DA151DB0D320C49" esri_qref=3D"no">
<p id=3D"GUID-7B2FD517-98D5-4297-BDC2-953D7961E1F5">The <span purpose=3D"gp=
toolref">Surface Parameters</span> tool provides a newer implementation of =
slope and is recommended to be used instead of the <span purpose=3D"gptoolr=
ef">Slope</span> tool. The <span purpose=3D"gptoolref">Slope</span> tool fi=
ts a plane to the nine local cells, but a plane may not be a good descripto=
r of the landscape and may mask or exaggerate natural variations of interes=
t. The <span purpose=3D"gptoolref">Surface Parameters</span> tool fits a su=
rface to the neighborhood of cells instead of a plane, which provides a mor=
e natural fit to the terrain.</p><p id=3D"GUID-22C7CC31-4498-4FBB-B30B-021B=
A410D95F">The <span purpose=3D"gptoolref">Slope</span> tool uses a 3 by 3 w=
indow of cells to compute the value, while the <span purpose=3D"gptoolref">=
Surface Parameters</span> tool allows window sizes from 3 by 3 to 15 by 15 =
cells. Larger window sizes are useful with high resolution elevation data t=
o capture land surface processes at an appropriate scale. The <span purpose=
=3D"gptoolref">Surface Parameters</span> tool also provides an adaptive win=
dow option that evaluates the local variability of the terrain and identifi=
es the largest appropriate neighborhood size for each cell. This can be use=
ful with gradual homogeneous terrain interrupted by streams, roads, or shar=
p breaks in slope.</p><p id=3D"GUID-62D05767-42AC-4712-9895-C84112ACADBB">Y=
ou can continue to use the traditional approach of the <span purpose=3D"gpt=
oolref">Slope</span> tool if you need the results to exactly match previous=
 tool runs or if fast processing time is more important than a better algor=
ithm.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_B9A851967F3041D58959BBC5C4B2D6=
C4" esri_qref=3D"yes"><p id=3D"GUID-A8531783-178F-4EE1-9474-0CB4F21C7D41" c=
onrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-8AEC1DBB-8903-46=
87-8FBF-33615219FE36">This tool uses a 3 by 3 cell moving window to process=
 the data. If the processing cell is NoData, the output for that location w=
ill be NoData.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_3DD64A6D8840445F9E09434B6B8A98=
2D" esri_qref=3D"yes"><p id=3D"GUID-66C42103-7E8D-45D2-831A-CD7ABCD657AF" c=
onrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-B91C4907-0825-46=
4E-A127-09FD95AAEBEA">Of the eight cells neighboring the processing cell, t=
his tool requires that at least seven of them have a valid value. If there =
are fewer than seven valid cells, the calculation will not be performed, an=
d the output at that processing cell will be NoData.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_18684476D1F24AEEA11BA55CF75A72=
34" esri_qref=3D"yes"><p id=3D"GUID-2EA60768-96E7-4E7E-A22D-7C1F3E0EDD05" c=
onrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-16D9D403-AB86-4F=
0C-98DE-799AAD44D8DE">The cells in the outermost rows and columns of the ou=
tput raster will be NoData. This is because along the boundary of the input=
 dataset, those cells do not have enough valid neighbors.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"GUID-3A8BE7C4-83B0-4026-A511-09BBFD3F0792=
" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-5403E9AB-127C-4E28-A817-73060CDD5B02">The =
range of values in the output depends on the type of measurement units.=20
</p><ul purpose=3D"ul" id=3D"UL_5C3065174BD74CC0B5AC231F994C11C9"><li purpo=
se=3D"li" id=3D"LI_56FA772138884130880DE7CCF4CB0CB6">For degrees, the range=
 of slope values is 0 to 90.</li><li purpose=3D"li" id=3D"LI_F6FF7F1310164B=
3BB056C6CB03C21A38">For percent rise, the range is 0 to essentially infinit=
y. A flat surface is 0 percent, a 45 degree surface is 100 percent, and as =
the surface becomes more vertical, the percent rise becomes increasingly la=
rger.</li></ul><p></p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"GUID-D0E07A5C-FE09-4429-95C0-0D8066B09FFF=
" esri_qref=3D"yes"><p id=3D"GUID-B26002E4-B5D7-42C9-99C0-D3D4AF7C9031">For=
 the planar method, the use of a z-factor is essential for correct slope ca=
lculations when the surface (vertical) z-units are expressed in units diffe=
rent from the ground x,y units. The <span class=3D"uicontrol">Z factor</spa=
n> parameter will be enabled only when the planar method is selected.</p></=
li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_B31D04D3A83349078B6D6DC28F2530=
9F" conrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/ESRI_USAGE_2FC44=
999A93848E8ABC368045BA29025" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-5CE22BE2-DAB2-4=
3BE-8DBA-478CF87E4CDB">For the geodesic method, specifying the surface z-un=
it ensures the accuracy of the output. The <span class=3D"uicontrol">Z unit=
</span> parameter will be enabled only when the geodesic method is selected=
.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_69B4A02DF7F3406BA413DE99089310=
10" conrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/ESRI_USAGE_C5B93=
6A561EC4D08912D7CE8C932A7FE" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-ABECB1CD-2CA1-4=
287-AAF8-6131F7B3DAF5">If a z-unit is available in the <a class=3D"xref xre=
f" esrisubtype=3D"extrel" hrefpfx=3D"/en/pro-app/3.4/help/mapping" href=3D"=
https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/3.4/help/mapping/properties/vertical-coor=
dinate-systems.htm">vertical coordinate system</a> of the input raster, it =
will be applied automatically. It is recommended that you define a z-unit f=
or the input raster if it is missing. You can use the <span purpose=3D"gpto=
olref"><a class=3D"xref xref" esrisubtype=3D"extrel" hrefpfx=3D"/en/pro-app=
/3.4/tool-reference" href=3D"https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/3.4/tool-ref=
erence/data-management/define-projection.htm#GUID-0CFF4F70-D6F1-4C2F-BF07-C=
2FC7A46C195">Define Projection</a></span> tool to specify a z-unit. If it i=
s undefined, meter will be used by default.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_36DCE2E16972472D99C43493117C19=
E3" conrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/ESRI_USAGE_68617=
3210EE44119B4714D3781AD3BD7" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-82C29F3B-24EC-4=
555-BDBD-605257B53699">When the input raster needs to be resampled, the bil=
inear technique will be used. An example of when an input raster may be res=
ampled is when the output coordinate system, extent, or cell size is differ=
ent from that of the input.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_81B84AF5222E4A3CBA839C214D6A46=
A4" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-AC8FF185-002A-4D40-A526-E4F545E6DF69" co=
nrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-2CAB774D-D263-43E=
9-A646-31910B800E1B">If the <span class=3D"uicontrol">Input raster</span> p=
arameter value is high resolution with a cell size of less than a few meter=
s, or particularly noisy, consider using the <span purpose=3D"gptoolref">Su=
rface Parameters</span> tool and its user-defined neighborhood distance opt=
ion instead of the immediate 3 by 3 neighborhood of this tool. Using a larg=
er neighborhood can minimize the effect of noisy surfaces. Using a larger n=
eighborhood can also better represent landforms and surface characteristics=
 when using high resolution surfaces.</p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_BD5F2C68BCBA449B8EE17DA2354F6B=
A7" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-ABE85098-325B-4B13-BE6B-7CAC17E73745" co=
nrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A26DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-8707FA10-0CA6-4A7=
C-858A-D2E6CF53B77A">This tool can be GPU accelerated, which means that if =
a compatible graphics processing unit (GPU) is available on your system, it=
 will be used to enhance the performance of the tool. Use the <span class=
=3D"uicontrol">Target device for analysis</span> (<span class=3D"usertext">=
analysis_target_device</span> in Python) parameter to control whether the G=
PU or CPU will be used to run the tool.</p>
<p id=3D"GUID-684CB85B-5C60-4D8B-B6C2-DE205D548D7D" conrefsub=3D"GUID-E42A2=
6DB-DC07-403E-86CE-84F0E2D4535F/GUID-615A998A-7C1C-4C9E-866D-C2A5AFC01263">=
<span class=3D"ph">See <a class=3D"xref xref" href=3D"https://pro.arcgis.co=
m/en/pro-app/3.4/tool-reference/spatial-analyst/gpu-processing-with-spatial=
-analyst.htm">GPU processing with Spatial Analyst</a> for details on compat=
ible GPUs, configuring and working with GPU devices, as well as troubleshoo=
ting tips.</span></p></li>
<li purpose=3D"gptoolusage" id=3D"ESRI_USAGE_56679762D22942F6AE2D2EC051F183=
70" conrefsub=3D"GUID-D37B28FC-9EA6-4D59-A998-409DC0CFC7FB/ESRI_USAGE_C8807=
1227A294E588512DBC5F3DC5847" esri_qref=3D"no"><p id=3D"GUID-9BCA59F5-2D99-4=
E53-9E7A-5A593ACFEF44">See <a class=3D"xref xref" href=3D"https://pro.arcgi=
s.com/en/pro-app/3.4/tool-reference/spatial-analyst/analysis-environments-a=
nd-spatial-analyst.htm">Analysis environments and Spatial Analyst</a> for a=
dditional details on the geoprocessing environments that apply to this tool=
.</p></li>
</ul></div>

